44
00:03:10,692 --> 00:03:12,794
They need to feel good and have fun.

45
00:03:14,145 --> 00:03:18,527
And a game as a service also needs a recurring source of revenue

46
00:03:18,527 --> 00:03:21,929
to support the game's development cost over the long run.

47
00:03:21,929 --> 00:03:29,392
Usually in the gaming world, we see these two components as direct opposites.

48
00:03:29,392 --> 00:03:34,175
We have a fear of backlash, like for myself as a creative,

49
00:03:34,175 --> 00:03:38,977
when we think about making money and monetization,

50
00:03:38,977 --> 00:03:41,098
we think of it as an evil feature.

51
00:03:41,098 --> 00:03:43,039
Let's not put that in the game.

52
00:03:44,303 --> 00:03:53,692
And believe me, it's not always easy to be the person in charge of thinking about what monetization features we need to implement.

53
00:03:53,692 --> 00:03:57,195
As Dave said, it's often seen as something a bit dirty.

54
00:03:57,195 --> 00:04:00,999
But the thing is, if we don't make money, it's not going to work.

55
00:04:00,999 --> 00:04:04,181
We need to make money to keep supporting the game's development costs.

56
00:04:07,321 --> 00:04:11,463
And with too much focus on making money

57
00:04:11,463 --> 00:04:15,144
and on the source of revenue, the players might leave

58
00:04:15,144 --> 00:04:17,385
and without any players, the game is dead.

59
00:04:17,385 --> 00:04:21,567
So spoiler alert, we have a live game

60
00:04:21,567 --> 00:04:23,428
with microtransactions.

61
00:04:23,428 --> 00:04:28,290
So we have an in-game store and we also have a battle pass.

62
00:04:28,290 --> 00:04:32,292
And at the same time, over its four years of existence,

63
00:04:32,292 --> 00:04:36,313
Dead by Daylight has seen over 20 million players

64
00:04:37,231 --> 00:04:40,233
an average of 2.7 millions of monthly active users,

65
00:04:40,233 --> 00:04:46,596
has consistently been in Steam's top 10 most played games since launch,

66
00:04:46,596 --> 00:04:52,960
the dev team has also grown from around 30 devs at launch to around 200 devs today,

67
00:04:52,960 --> 00:05:00,044
and Dead by Daylight is also the most streamed horror game on Twitch.

68
00:05:00,044 --> 00:05:03,166
For us, the key was really to understand that

69
00:05:03,166 --> 00:05:06,908
entertaining players and making money aren't necessarily opposed.

70
00:05:08,973 --> 00:05:12,435
We've put the conflicting elements on the side,

71
00:05:12,435 --> 00:05:15,696
and we realized that really these two facets

72
00:05:15,696 --> 00:05:18,578
of making the game would create a synergy.

73
00:05:18,578 --> 00:05:20,999
One would feed the other.

74
00:05:20,999 --> 00:05:23,821
We realized that if we wanted to support the game

75
00:05:23,821 --> 00:05:26,202
over the years with a source of revenue,

76
00:05:26,202 --> 00:05:29,404
we would need to make the source of revenue

77
00:05:29,404 --> 00:05:30,284
a joy for the players.

78
00:05:31,044 --> 00:05:34,166
So the key here was to add monetization feature

79
00:05:34,166 --> 00:05:37,009
that would add to the fun aspect of the game.

80
00:05:37,009 --> 00:05:40,511
We did that with a lot of soul searching

81
00:05:40,511 --> 00:05:46,536
and we sat down together and we found four core values

82
00:05:46,536 --> 00:05:49,077
that we would use anytime we would create

83
00:05:49,077 --> 00:05:51,419
a monetization feature in Dead by Daylight.

84
00:05:51,419 --> 00:05:54,682
And these four values we are sure would work

85
00:05:54,682 --> 00:05:56,823
for any game as a service title.

86
00:05:56,823 --> 00:06:00,486
They are valuableness, respect.

87
00:06:01,983 --> 00:06:04,625
generosity and transparency.

88
00:06:04,625 --> 00:06:09,509
Okay, so let's start with valuableness.

89
00:06:09,509 --> 00:06:13,392
What we mean by valuableness is three things.

90
00:06:13,392 --> 00:06:17,014
First, don't remove value to sell.

91
00:06:17,014 --> 00:06:21,918
Focus on quality versus quantity and enrich the game.

92
00:06:21,918 --> 00:06:24,520
So if my goal is to make money,

93
00:06:24,520 --> 00:06:27,882
the instinct would be to look at what players need the most

94
00:06:27,882 --> 00:06:29,123
and sell this thing, right?

95
00:06:29,735 --> 00:06:35,646
So if you need a sword to fight a monster, it's easy. I'll give your sword a durability so that

96
00:06:35,646 --> 00:06:41,576
you have to buy a new one. And I'm even gonna make the sword more powerful. Easy money, right?

97
00:06:43,810 --> 00:06:49,696
Well, we decided not to do this as firstly, this would make our game very expensive to play,

98
00:06:49,696 --> 00:06:55,761
and secondly, it would make the game even pay to win in our case because you play against other

99
00:06:55,761 --> 00:07:00,445
players. It's important to make money, but not at the detriment of players having fun and the game's

100
00:07:00,445 --> 00:07:07,712
DNA. Ultimately, retention is at the heart of how well your monetization is doing. So the key

101
00:07:07,712 --> 00:07:10,334
takeaway here is don't remove value to sell.

102
00:07:11,009 --> 00:07:14,812
There are other ways, like selling cosmetics for example.

103
00:07:14,812 --> 00:07:23,959
Cosmetics are optional, but players usually love them because it allows them to customize their beloved characters.

104
00:07:23,959 --> 00:07:36,349
With monetization, if you don't know where to start, characters customization is the type of monetization feature that usually works well because it is additive of value.

105
00:07:36,349 --> 00:07:39,752
So, we decided to sell cosmetic items in the store. Cool!

106
00:07:40,408 --> 00:07:44,170
Now, our next challenge was to fill the store with content.

107
00:07:44,170 --> 00:07:50,253
We have tons of different killers and survivors, so let's create lots of color variations of our

108
00:07:50,253 --> 00:07:57,996
characters and also let's create tons of weapon skins. Maybe we could invest in tools that can

109
00:07:57,996 --> 00:08:02,398
automate this process. Filling the store that way would be super efficient.

110
00:08:03,793 --> 00:08:08,116
Well, even if it might sound efficient to create cosmetics that way,

111
00:08:08,116 --> 00:08:14,359
we decided not to do this and to focus our efforts on creating very high-quality cosmetics

112
00:08:14,359 --> 00:08:17,681
rather than focusing on quantity.

113
00:08:17,681 --> 00:08:23,164
Why? Because we, devs, would love efficiency to equate efficacy,

114
00:08:23,164 --> 00:08:29,408
but with cosmetic items, what really matters for players is the quality, not the quantity.

115
00:08:30,645 --> 00:08:37,389
So from our experience, WhatSells is not a store with tons of color options and a wide range of t-shirts,

116
00:08:37,389 --> 00:08:39,290
but a store with high quality items.

117
00:08:39,290 --> 00:08:46,354
And from our experience, what works for us is high quality cosmetics that sell a fantasy.

118
00:08:46,354 --> 00:08:52,097
They look way more interesting for our players as they allow them to express their personality.

119
00:08:52,097 --> 00:08:55,920
Also, they are more fun to produce for our teams of artists.

120
00:08:57,830 --> 00:09:03,094
The dream of playing a specific character is at the core of these cosmetics.

121
00:09:03,094 --> 00:09:10,379
They have a strong fantasy that goes beyond gameplay purposes.

122
00:09:10,379 --> 00:09:16,723
So being able to customize your character allows the player to express their own personality,

123
00:09:16,723 --> 00:09:21,926
and it also allows them to play very specific roles, like specific characters that exist in

124
00:09:21,926 --> 00:09:26,229
franchises, for example, and that's super important and will

125
00:09:26,616 --> 00:09:30,179
is adds a lot of value to the cosmetic.

126
00:09:30,179 --> 00:09:34,582
They also enrich the game universe.

127
00:09:34,582 --> 00:09:36,664
They add variety to the game.

128
00:09:36,664 --> 00:09:38,866
They enrich the visual.

129
00:09:38,866 --> 00:09:40,707
The more cosmetic that we add to the game,

130
00:09:40,707 --> 00:09:41,908
especially high-quality one,

131
00:09:41,908 --> 00:09:44,450
it means that you'll see

132
00:09:44,450 --> 00:09:47,272
more differences in the game world every match you play.

133
00:09:47,272 --> 00:09:52,256
There's also something very special we do in DbD.

134
00:09:52,256 --> 00:09:54,478
The cosmetics are not

135
00:09:55,064 --> 00:10:00,107
only just visually stunning, they also come with a story.

136
00:10:00,107 --> 00:10:02,648
And it's a chance for us, it's a platform,

137
00:10:02,648 --> 00:10:04,649
to tell more stories about our character

138
00:10:04,649 --> 00:10:08,131
and deepen the lore so that the players

139
00:10:08,131 --> 00:10:10,413
can know more about their favorite characters.

140
00:10:10,413 --> 00:10:12,074
Obviously, there are some limits.

141
00:10:12,074 --> 00:10:18,817
We found our own limits because we're doing a horror game.

142
00:10:18,817 --> 00:10:19,898
There's some.

143
00:10:21,153 --> 00:10:25,416
things we have to refuse as cosmetic item,

144
00:10:25,416 --> 00:10:28,379
even though we know they would be super popular

145
00:10:28,379 --> 00:10:29,440
and they would sell well.

146
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:34,504
For example, we could have a demand

147
00:10:34,504 --> 00:10:40,529
to make a grim killer looking aesthetic item for a survivor

148
00:10:40,529 --> 00:10:41,390
and vice versa.

149
00:10:41,390 --> 00:10:45,253
We could have like a very funny or sexy in this example.

150
00:10:45,793 --> 00:10:50,255
skins that are requested on our characters.

