00:16:11,510 --> 00:16:15,692
Should we go with loot boxes or a fixed price?

240
00:16:15,692 --> 00:16:18,234
The logic to maximize the price of an outfit

241
00:16:18,234 --> 00:16:20,315
would be to sell them through loot boxes.

242
00:16:20,315 --> 00:16:23,317
Loot boxes would allow us to have some of our outfits

243
00:16:23,317 --> 00:16:25,799
valued at hundreds, even thousands of dollars

244
00:16:25,799 --> 00:16:28,461
because we could make the odds of dropping

245
00:16:28,461 --> 00:16:31,603
some cosmetics super, super small.

246
00:16:31,603 --> 00:16:32,623
Easy money, right?

247
00:16:34,009 --> 00:16:38,332
Well, we decided not to sell loot boxes, but to offer an à la carte store instead,

248
00:16:38,332 --> 00:16:47,079
even if it meant generating less revenue, because we find this model more respectful of our players' wallet.

249
00:16:47,079 --> 00:16:50,201
Players can purchase the outfits they want.

250
00:16:50,201 --> 00:16:54,584
They can even purchase the individual piece of an outfit if they wish.

251
00:16:54,584 --> 00:17:02,390
And we also wanted our cool cosmetics to be accessible to the many, even to the smaller spenders.

252
00:17:03,237 --> 00:17:09,861
In Dead by Daylight, there are four tiers of outfits from common to very rare.

253
00:17:09,861 --> 00:17:12,823
Our outfits cost from $1.2 to an average of $10.

254
00:17:12,823 --> 00:17:19,228
And since players can purchase the pieces individually, our items

255
00:17:19,228 --> 00:17:19,928
actually go from 50 cents to $4.

256
00:17:19,928 --> 00:17:22,130
The other component is respect their time.

257
00:17:22,130 --> 00:17:25,632
We talked about a battle pass earlier, right?

258
00:17:25,632 --> 00:17:30,555
So a battle pass system, you have to play to unlock.

259
00:17:31,070 --> 00:17:37,274
tiers to be able to unlock some rewards. The more you play, the more you'll unlock. You can buy the

260
00:17:37,274 --> 00:17:43,438
tiers to unlock more content if you don't have the time to play for it. So an instinct here would be

261
00:17:43,438 --> 00:17:51,544
that to optimize the revenue, we should make it a super long grind to be able to get everything.

262
00:17:51,544 --> 00:17:55,227
Easy money, again.

263
00:17:55,819 --> 00:18:06,522
But really, this is also wrong for us. It goes against respect of our player. So here's how we

264
00:18:06,522 --> 00:18:16,104
do it instead. So first of all, we use the data out of the playtime of the players to understand

265
00:18:16,613 --> 00:18:21,235
what's an average player in Dead by Daylight and how much time they have to spend on the game

266
00:18:21,235 --> 00:18:26,498
on average. So here the idea was not to push everybody to play more to be able to grind

267
00:18:26,498 --> 00:18:33,941
everything. So we found out that an hour a day was the average for our players and so we made sure

268
00:18:33,941 --> 00:18:39,383
that the whole rift was accessible to everyone and that most players would be able to go through it

269
00:18:39,383 --> 00:18:45,586
and unlock cool content. We've also took the decision to put some of the high-valued cosmetics

270
00:18:46,458 --> 00:18:52,041
in the first years of the battle pass so that a lot of players would be able to get them.

271
00:18:52,041 --> 00:19:00,487
Let's talk about some of our learnings now. First, we did not see backlash when we introduced our

272
00:19:00,487 --> 00:19:05,710
in-game store two years post-launch. Same for our battle pass introduced almost four years

273
00:19:05,710 --> 00:19:10,173
post-launch. And for the few negative comments we could see on our socials,

274
00:19:10,967 --> 00:19:16,469
We didn't even had time to react because we saw 10 times more players defending and supporting us.

275
00:19:16,469 --> 00:19:22,452
And I think that when you design monetization respectfully, this is what you get.

276
00:19:22,452 --> 00:19:24,953
You turn players into ambassadors.

277
00:19:24,953 --> 00:19:29,375
And for having worked on live games for quite some time now,

278
00:19:29,375 --> 00:19:35,278
I can tell you that this is the position you always want to be in.

279
00:19:35,278 --> 00:19:40,020
And instead of fearing backlash, we actually saw lots of positive word of mouth.

280
00:19:41,234 --> 00:19:52,676
Every time a competitor does something that has to do with micro transactions that gets players angry, we see lots of players praising us.

281
00:19:52,676 --> 00:19:59,058
Also, having a respectful monetization design helps to get the buying from our dev team.

282
00:19:59,058 --> 00:20:07,780
As Dave said at the beginning of the presentation, it is very important that your dev team doesn't see monetization features as evil features.

283
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:12,463
So to sum up this value of respect,

284
00:20:12,463 --> 00:20:13,844
it may sound obvious,

285
00:20:13,844 --> 00:20:15,806
but you need to respect players of all types

286
00:20:15,806 --> 00:20:18,868
and you need to ease their chosen way

287
00:20:18,868 --> 00:20:20,590
to access what is fun in your game.

288
00:20:20,590 --> 00:20:23,032
Next value is generosity.

289
00:20:23,032 --> 00:20:26,995
And what we mean by that is inclusiveness.

290
00:20:26,995 --> 00:20:31,019
So have the most player as possible

291
00:20:31,019 --> 00:20:33,781
to experience what is fun in the game,

292
00:20:33,781 --> 00:20:35,323
to have access of what is fun in the game.

293
00:20:35,943 --> 00:20:39,286
And also it's to get more than your money's worth

294
00:20:39,286 --> 00:20:44,651
when you do decide to buy something.

295
00:20:44,651 --> 00:20:48,134
We put our hearts and soul into these products

296
00:20:48,134 --> 00:20:49,835
that we're making.

297
00:20:49,835 --> 00:20:52,238
It costs a lot of money, a lot of resources,

298
00:20:52,238 --> 00:20:53,018
a lot of energy.

299
00:20:53,395 --> 00:20:55,296
to create awesome content.

300
00:20:55,296 --> 00:20:58,197
So the reflex here is to say that every gameplay,

301
00:20:58,197 --> 00:21:01,778
every concept, every model, every marketing bit

302
00:21:01,778 --> 00:21:06,500
that we need to do should bring back profit.

303
00:21:06,500 --> 00:21:09,141
So we should put a price tag on everything.

304
00:21:09,141 --> 00:21:13,503
And so we would make the most money as possible.

305
00:21:13,503 --> 00:21:18,686
But this is not a good way to do it for us.

306
00:21:18,686 --> 00:21:20,947
We've decided to do things otherwise.

307
00:21:21,525 --> 00:21:24,426
And we've decided to be more generous

308
00:21:24,426 --> 00:21:31,628
So here's you can see on the right is a near distant shard and that's our soft currency. It's a currency that you can

309
00:21:31,628 --> 00:21:38,230
Grind through the game. So just by playing you unlock this currency and it allows you to unlock and

310
00:21:38,230 --> 00:21:40,670
Play all of our original characters

311
00:21:40,670 --> 00:21:46,272
Also 60 to 70 percent of our store is

312
00:21:46,272 --> 00:21:50,053
unlockable with the soft currency

313
00:21:51,871 --> 00:21:54,993
So this is great because for the characters, for example,

314
00:21:54,993 --> 00:22:00,675
a player that decides to not spend a dime and just play the game,

315
00:22:00,675 --> 00:22:02,816
will eventually unlock new characters,

316
00:22:02,816 --> 00:22:05,098
which will add to his experience,

317
00:22:05,098 --> 00:22:07,899
but it will also add to the other player's experience

318
00:22:07,899 --> 00:22:09,620
because it will add variety to the game.

319
00:22:09,620 --> 00:22:14,742
So it just makes for a more healthy experience in the game.

320
00:22:14,742 --> 00:22:19,985
For the skins, we find out that as a reward,

321
00:22:20,517 --> 00:22:24,438
for your play time, unlocking a skin and be able to show it off

322
00:22:24,438 --> 00:22:30,980
is very meaningful to players.

323
00:22:30,980 --> 00:22:36,362
Now when it comes to the battle pass, we apply the same value, generosity.

324
00:22:36,362 --> 00:22:39,163
So our battle pass contains 70 chills, 70 levels.

325
00:22:39,163 --> 00:22:44,184
And I remember having this discussion with Dave that

326
00:22:44,184 --> 00:22:46,985
70 rewards, it's a lot of content to produce.

327
00:22:47,789 --> 00:22:55,391
So our instinct was to either raise the price of the battle pass or just fill it with rubbish.

328
00:22:55,391 --> 00:23:02,052
But we felt that both solutions were unacceptable for us. So we decided to sell the battle pass at

329
00:23:02,052 --> 00:23:07,534
$10 and be generous with the content that is included in the battle pass even if,

330
00:23:07,534 --> 00:23:14,815
monetarily speaking, it made no sense. The bet here was to get players excited and bet on retention too.

331
00:23:14,815 --> 00:23:17,016
So we are not saying that

332
00:23:17,423 --> 00:23:25,769
Our 70 tiers of rewards only contain awesome rewards, but for $10 players can earn over $200 worth of content.

333
00:23:25,769 --> 00:23:35,997
If they finish the battle pass, they also can get their $10 back since $10 worth of Oryx cells, our hard currency, are included in the battle pass.

334
00:23:35,997 --> 00:23:43,963
And for the players who do not wish to spend, by simply playing the game regularly, they can get over $35 worth of value.

335
00:23:47,836 --> 00:23:56,299
Also another choice that we've made is that there's no pressure to play the Archive and

336
00:23:56,299 --> 00:23:58,519
to unlock things in the Battle Pass.

337
00:23:58,519 --> 00:24:04,641
All the challenges, so the gameplay that comes along with a tome in the Archive, all the

338
00:24:04,641 --> 00:24:09,303
narrative assets are available for everyone forever.

339
00:24:09,303 --> 00:24:15,365
So even the new player that comes in has 20-30 hours of free content that's available.

340
00:24:16,124 --> 00:24:19,686
for each archive that we release.

341
00:24:19,686 --> 00:24:23,427
Learnings out of this value of generosity.

342
00:24:23,427 --> 00:24:25,088
First of all, is that it's clear for

343
00:24:25,088 --> 00:24:27,829
us that it leads to increased play time.

344
00:24:27,829 --> 00:24:30,410
We can see here that in the graph,

345
00:24:30,410 --> 00:24:31,631
as soon as the store launched,

346
00:24:31,631 --> 00:24:35,172
the average session duration went up.

347
00:24:35,172 --> 00:24:37,413
People play more, they want to get that currency,

348
00:24:37,413 --> 00:24:39,054
they want to unlock cosmetics.

349
00:24:39,054 --> 00:24:44,396
This second graph is also super interesting because we can see

350
00:24:44,396 --> 00:24:45,317
that in the weeks.

351
00:24:45,667 --> 00:24:50,270
before and the weeks after the battle pass,

352
00:24:50,270 --> 00:24:53,353
and of course, during the battle pass as well,

353
00:24:53,353 --> 00:24:56,915
the average session duration also went up.

354
00:24:56,915 --> 00:24:58,997
So people are playing more

355
00:24:58,997 --> 00:25:01,879
to unlock the content of the archive.

356
00:25:01,879 --> 00:25:04,541
Seriously, there's not a lot of features that,

357
00:25:04,541 --> 00:25:06,603
I mean, monetized or not,

358
00:25:06,603 --> 00:25:10,146
that is able to generate such an impact on engagement.

359
00:25:13,157 --> 00:25:20,220
Making characters accessible encourage a better meta and diversity.

360
00:25:20,220 --> 00:25:29,223
So the fact that the players are able to unlock freely the characters is super healthy for the type of game that we're doing.

361
00:25:29,223 --> 00:25:35,066
Another learning, allowing players to unlock content with playtime is also good for revenue.

362
00:25:35,066 --> 00:25:41,468
We know that players playing with more characters buy more skins, and this goes up exponentially.

363
00:25:42,258 --> 00:25:46,700
It is logic. Characters are a platform for cosmetics.

364
00:25:46,700 --> 00:25:51,702
So in other words, our revenue goes up with the amount of characters owned,

365
00:25:51,702 --> 00:25:56,544
so facilitating the access to characters was the right bet for us.

366
00:25:56,544 --> 00:26:04,107
Our Battle Pass, when it is active, generates an average of 20% incremental daily average revenue per user overall.

367
00:26:04,107 --> 00:26:10,410
So in addition to seeing players play more, players also end up spending more.

368
00:26:11,559 --> 00:26:14,181
So Arbed was right about the battle pass.

369
00:26:14,181 --> 00:26:19,166
Generosity led to incremental revenue and play time.

370
00:26:19,166 --> 00:26:21,448
So to sum up, be generous,

371
00:26:21,448 --> 00:26:24,871
make sure that all sorts of players, monetizing or not,

372
00:26:24,871 --> 00:26:28,474
are included in the whole game

373
00:26:28,474 --> 00:26:29,995
and that they are happy and engaged.

374
00:26:32,137 --> 00:26:36,879
because at the end, what you will end up having is a very virtuous loop.

375
00:26:36,879 --> 00:26:39,840
I remember us looking at each other with Dave,

376
00:26:39,840 --> 00:26:43,241
and when we saw the result, we felt very happy

377
00:26:43,241 --> 00:26:45,982
because players that are happy will stay longer

378
00:26:45,982 --> 00:26:48,083
and will eventually monetize,

379
00:26:48,083 --> 00:26:51,844
and players who monetize are even more engaged and stay longer in the game.

380
00:26:51,844 --> 00:26:53,444
So it's really perfect.

381
00:26:53,444 --> 00:26:58,146
So now let's talk about our fourth value, transparency.

382
00:26:58,146 --> 00:26:59,726
So what does it mean for us?

383
00:26:59,726 --> 00:27:02,027
First, communicate your intent.

384
00:27:02,870 --> 00:27:06,433
Always explain why and acknowledge your mistakes.

385
00:27:06,433 --> 00:27:08,274
So if we go back two years in time,

386
00:27:08,274 --> 00:27:09,695
I remember Dave and I wondering

387
00:27:09,695 --> 00:27:13,138
how to communicate our store to our players.

388
00:27:13,138 --> 00:27:16,580
We were a bit honestly frightened by that.

389
00:27:16,580 --> 00:27:20,343
But what we did is that we wrote a blog post

390
00:27:20,343 --> 00:27:23,286
titled our store philosophies

391
00:27:23,286 --> 00:27:24,927
that we shared with our community

392
00:27:24,927 --> 00:27:27,829
before the store even came out.

393
00:27:27,829 --> 00:27:29,490
We basically explained to them

394
00:27:29,490 --> 00:27:32,393
almost everything we explained to you in this GDC talk.

395
00:27:33,430 --> 00:27:35,992
Very transparently, we detailed our store pillars,

396
00:27:35,992 --> 00:27:38,993
how our currencies work, and how much everything costs.

397
00:27:38,993 --> 00:27:42,295
And above all, we explained to our players

398
00:27:42,295 --> 00:27:44,756
why we introduced Assore.

399
00:27:44,756 --> 00:27:48,898
Our in-game store was presented at the same time

400
00:27:48,898 --> 00:27:51,559
as Dead by Daylight's Year 3 roadmap.

401
00:27:51,559 --> 00:27:54,080
So allow me to read a section of our blog post to you.

402
00:27:55,550 --> 00:27:58,571
We are very excited to start Dead by Daylight Year 3 with you

403
00:27:58,571 --> 00:28:01,532
and want you to know that the launch of Chapter 8 in June

404
00:28:01,532 --> 00:28:04,312
is just the beginning of what we want to do.

405
00:28:04,312 --> 00:28:08,213
We believe that this game will have more anniversaries to celebrate

406
00:28:08,213 --> 00:28:10,294
and we are eager to continue to support the game

407
00:28:10,294 --> 00:28:12,374
as the Dead by Daylight community grows.

408
00:28:12,374 --> 00:28:15,875
We would like to give an early thank you

409
00:28:15,875 --> 00:28:18,756
to all the players who will be buying cosmetic items

410
00:28:18,756 --> 00:28:22,897
as this is what will allow us to support our ambitions for the future.

411
00:28:24,537 --> 00:28:28,180
So if you intend to add microtransactions in your game,

412
00:28:28,180 --> 00:28:32,283
telling players why you need them is super important.

413
00:28:32,283 --> 00:28:33,765
When players buy a cosmetic item,

414
00:28:33,765 --> 00:28:37,788
they invest in the game and the dev team.

415
00:28:37,788 --> 00:28:39,669
For Dead by Daylight players,

416
00:28:39,669 --> 00:28:41,911
the introduction of an in-game store

417
00:28:41,911 --> 00:28:45,014
had in some ways become a promise of a future

418
00:28:45,014 --> 00:28:46,915
for the development of the game.

419
00:28:49,010 --> 00:28:52,753
And what worked well for us, and I think is really important,

420
00:28:52,753 --> 00:28:55,456
is that you have to do this communication with your own voice.

421
00:28:55,456 --> 00:28:57,637
You need to be super candid about it.

422
00:28:57,637 --> 00:29:00,460
And when we did it, we had a live stream,

423
00:29:00,460 --> 00:29:04,523
but before that, we had a pre-recorded video made as well.

424
00:29:04,523 --> 00:29:08,646
And this was pretty cool because we had to work with the whole team

425
00:29:08,646 --> 00:29:10,508
to show these values and to show this plan,

426
00:29:10,508 --> 00:29:14,111
and we saw that they would get on board with what we were saying.

427
00:29:14,484 --> 00:29:17,406
So we knew at this point that it was going to work.

428
00:29:17,406 --> 00:29:19,327
If you can get your team on board 100%,

429
00:29:19,327 --> 00:29:24,290
it's gonna be far more easier than to get your community

430
00:29:24,290 --> 00:29:25,891
to understand what's going on.

431
00:29:25,891 --> 00:29:29,934
So in this process, as we said,

432
00:29:29,934 --> 00:29:32,896
we've also presented our year three roadmap.

433
00:29:32,896 --> 00:29:34,757
And it was a great exercise.

434
00:29:34,757 --> 00:29:36,778
We'd like to take some time to talk about

435
00:29:36,778 --> 00:29:38,720
some of the learning that we got from sharing

436
00:29:38,720 --> 00:29:40,461
our year three roadmap with our community.

437
00:29:41,245 --> 00:29:46,567
So we showed to our players one year of content, including new killers, new survival of the maps,

438
00:29:46,567 --> 00:29:50,650
as well as some changes and priorities we wanted to tackle.

439
00:29:50,650 --> 00:29:56,072
So showing your plans long in advance helps to get players excited about what's coming,

440
00:29:56,072 --> 00:30:02,075
even if it is not live yet. For example, we told our players in advance that we would reinforce

441
00:30:02,075 --> 00:30:07,578
our anti-cheat system, and even if it got released several months later,

442
00:30:07,578 --> 00:30:10,420
knowing it was coming helped to keep our players patient.

443
00:30:11,873 --> 00:30:19,619
More generally, it was the first time we told our community that we would keep supporting the game for years to come.

444
00:30:19,619 --> 00:30:26,905
And as a player, or even as a streamer, it sends a strong message that they can keep investing their time and money in our game

445
00:30:26,905 --> 00:30:31,328
because we, devs, are committed to keep investing in it as well.

446
00:30:31,328 --> 00:30:36,832
After all, why would we expect a player to commit his or her time and money in our game

447
00:30:36,832 --> 00:30:40,275
if we don't ourselves commit to keep investing in the game too?

448
00:30:41,100 --> 00:30:45,863
It can also help to structure production as it forces the dev team to think about the future.

449
00:30:45,863 --> 00:30:52,927
It forces us to think about what priorities we want to tackle next, which also makes us work in the right order.

450
00:30:52,927 --> 00:30:58,710
And having some dates laid out in the future also allows us to retro-plan every phase of production,

451
00:30:58,710 --> 00:31:07,755
from design kick-off to official release, including dedicated time for QA and dedicated time for live testing on our public test environment, for example.

452
00:31:08,559 --> 00:31:11,361
So having a roadmap has many advantages.

453
00:31:11,361 --> 00:31:14,483
But this is definitely not for everyone.

454
00:31:14,483 --> 00:31:16,985
It might be more difficult for smaller studios

455
00:31:16,985 --> 00:31:20,607
or for a game that's not live yet.

456
00:31:20,607 --> 00:31:22,849
Because yeah, when you're communicating this roadmap

457
00:31:22,849 --> 00:31:25,571
through the whole world, you're committing to the content

458
00:31:25,571 --> 00:31:26,271
you're promising.

459
00:31:26,271 --> 00:31:29,113
Also, you're creating expectation.

460
00:31:29,113 --> 00:31:32,836
If you are not delivering on the content you've promised,

461
00:31:32,836 --> 00:31:35,698
of course, you're going to disappoint your community.

462
00:31:35,698 --> 00:31:37,559
You're going to have to deal with that later.

463
00:31:38,348 --> 00:31:41,410
A word of advice here, the best thing is to stay high level

464
00:31:41,410 --> 00:31:43,552
when you're communicating about your roadmap,

465
00:31:43,552 --> 00:31:45,754
so that you don't create too much expectation.

466
00:31:45,754 --> 00:31:49,097
And also make sure that you tell your community

467
00:31:49,097 --> 00:31:50,518
that these things might change.

468
00:31:50,518 --> 00:31:55,202
Communicating your roadmap also creates a precedent.

469
00:31:55,202 --> 00:31:58,926
Every year when you present your new roadmap,

470
00:31:58,926 --> 00:32:03,229
there's gonna be a want that this roadmap

471
00:32:03,229 --> 00:32:05,491
is more awesome than the previous one.

472
00:32:06,279 --> 00:32:08,741
So that gets increasingly more difficult.

473
00:32:08,741 --> 00:32:13,664
